<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="text">
<PB REF="014737_0002_0F94DB51798AD1D8">
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q><BIBL>ROMANS VIII.31.</BIBL>
<P>What &s;hall we &s;ay to the&s;e Things?&mdash;If GOD be for us, who can be again&s;t us?</P></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P>FROM the words we may note,
<LIST>
<ITEM>I. <HI>The importance of GOD's being for us.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM>II. <HI>What mu&s;t ab&s;olutely be done on our part, that the ble&s;&s;ed GOD may be on our &s;ide, or for us.</HI></ITEM>
<ITEM>III. <HI>How ble&s;&s;ed it will be to have GOD for us.</HI></ITEM>
</LIST></P>
<P>AND here,</P>
<P N="1">I. <HI>The importance of GOD's being for us.</HI></P>
<P>WE have, my dear Countrymen, entered into the mo&s;t &s;olemn, weighty, and extraordinary affair, that ever concerned <HI>America</HI>; an affair that will termi|nate in our final ruin, unle&s;s GOD be for us.&mdash; We have though I tru&s;t with the greate&s;t reluctance, taken up arms again&s;t the King of <HI>Great-Britain,</HI> who is the mo&s;t powerful prince in the known world, who has been a terror to all nations, who is the &s;tronge&s;t by &s;ea, and can command the greate&s;t navy of any nation whatever; a great part of which is now employed in bringing &s;oldiers, arms, ammu|nition and <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 word"> to <HI>America,</HI> with a determination to &s;ubdue us&mdash;have taken <HI>Bo&s;ton,</HI> the metropolis of <HI>New-England</HI>&mdash;have made it a &s;trong garri&s;on to guard them&s;elves&mdash;many fir&s;t blocked in as pri&s;o|ners&mdash;others obliged to leave their plea&s;ant habita|tions;&mdash;have burned <HI>Charle&s;town,</HI> a very fine and beautiful place, to a&s;hes&mdash;cau&s;ed the inhabitants to
<PB N="3" REF="014737_0003_0F94DB523B7154B8">
<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="2 letters">ave their habitations in flames;&mdash;have proceeded <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="2 letters">rther&mdash;have burned <HI>Falmouth,</HI> a place of va&s;t value&mdash;men, women, and children, in the greate&s;t confu&s;ion and con&s;ternation, occa&s;ioned by the roar|ing of their cannon, the devouring flames of their buildings&mdash;obliged to leave their dwellings in ru|ins&mdash;have immediate orders to burn all the &s;ea-ports from thence to <HI>Carolina</HI>&mdash;will certainly execute their cruel de&s;ign, which in the i&s;&s;ue will damage <HI>America</HI> not le&s;s than 50 millions of money. Now all this will certainly be effected, unle&s;s GOD be for us.&mdash;To have this great and mighty nation again&s;t us, and the great and dreadful GOD again&s;t us too, mu&s;t be dreadful indeed! For if GOD be again&s;t us, all the victories we have already gained, will only &s;erve to augment their fury, and bring all the power and force of <HI>Great-Britain</HI> on us, and perhaps joined with the &s;trength of other nations.&mdash; If GOD be again&s;t us, all the wi&s;e con&s;ultations of a&s;&s;emblies and congre&s;&s;es will prove abortive, our armies will be defeated, our country will be ravaged, we &s;hall be de&s;troyed by the &s;word, by the famine, and by the pe&s;tilence; the &s;word without, and terror within, will con&s;ume us&mdash;a fire will be enkindled in his anger, that will burn to the lowe&s;t hell&mdash; He will &s;catter us into corners&mdash;he will cau&s;e the remembrance of us to cea&s;e, and deliver us up to the greate&s;t reproach&mdash;tho&s;e that hate us will rule over us, and we &s;hall be treated as the wor&s;t of rebels.&mdash;This will certainly be the fate of <HI>America,</HI> unle&s;s GOD be for us, and on our &s;ide.&mdash;Now, <HI>What &s;hall we &s;ay to the&s;e things? If GOD be for us,
<PB N="4" REF="014737_0004_0F94DB52FB4F9030">
who can be again&s;t us?</HI> And if he be again&s;t us who can be for us, that is able to deliver us?</P>
<P>Shewing the way, and the only way for the delive|rance of <HI>America</HI> from the mo&s;t di&s;tre&s;&s;ing calami|ties that ever befel any people.</P>
<P>THUS we &s;ee, my dear friends and countrymen, that it is all-important that GOD be for us. Which brings us to con&s;ider, in the</P>
<P N="2">II. Place, <HI>What mu&s;t ab&s;olutely be done on our part, that the ble&s;&s;ed GOD may be for us.</HI></P>
<P>AND here, <HI>Fir&s;t,</HI> Was is Liberty that fir&s;t cau&s;ed the &s;ettlement of this country?&mdash;Was this land de|&s;igned by God him&s;elf for a land of liberty?&mdash;Was this the tenor and condition of the grant of this country from God to our forefathers, that no tyrant &s;hould ever reign here?&mdash;Is this the only thing the Americans are &s;uing for?&mdash;Was it their a&s;&s;ert|ing their rights to this precious jewel, that has drawn the &s;word again&s;t us?&mdash;Is it liberty that has &s;et the nation in &s;uch a terrible convul&s;ion?&mdash;Then it will certainly appear, that all tho&s;e laws, cu&s;toms, and practices, that infringe on the liberties of man|kind, and are repugnant to the law of God, mu&s;t be done away. Every thing that has any tendency to bind the con&s;ciences of God's Children, of what name or denomination &s;oever, mu&s;t be done away. As we would have the Lord on our &s;ide, we mu&s;t &s;et at Liberty tho&s;e va&s;t numbers of <HI>Africans,</HI> which have &s;o long time been in&s;laved by us, who have as good a right to Liberty as we have&mdash;We mu&s;t no longer exerci&s;e that Cruelty and Barbarity towards
<PB N="5" REF="014737_0005_0F94DB53BA5BC608">
them, as we have heretofore done&mdash;We mu&s;t put a final &s;top to all vexatious Law &s;uits, and no longer exerci&s;e that Cruelty among our&s;elves that even heathens would not be found guilty of&mdash;We mu&s;t for ever cea&s;e from this &s;o ruinous a Practice&mdash;We mu&s;t be kind and benevolent to the Poor&mdash;help and de|liver them out of all their troubles and di&s;tre&s;&s;es&mdash; break every yoke, and every heavy burden, &amp; let the oppre&s;&s;ed go free. See I&s;a. 58, 7, and on&mdash;We mu&s;t be &s;incere in our endeavors for Liberty, without a|ny wicked or avaricious ends or de&s;igns for riches or honours to aggrandize our&s;elves or children&mdash; We mu&s;t faithfully improve all our &s;piritual privi|leges, and prize them above every thing el&s;e&mdash;We mu&s;t have as much zeal to improve them as we have to contend for them, and then the Lord will never &s;uffer them to be taken from us.&mdash;We mu&s;t heartily a&s;cribe the glory of all the victories obtain|ed by us, to GOD alone; and go, if called to it, again&s;t our enemies, as King <HI>David</HI> went again&s;t <HI>Goliah,</HI> in the name and &s;trength of the LORD GOD of I&s;rael&mdash;We mu&s;t continue that union and unani|mity that &s;ub&s;i&s;ts between the colonies, and unite, as one man, in putting away all tho&s;e &s;ins and abo|minations which is the cau&s;e of God's controver&s;y with us,&mdash;and continue to humble our &s;elves in the united public manner as was once appointed by the Grand Continental Congre&s;s; which was the mo&s;t extraordinary affair that ever happened in America: &s;ince which time we have been wonderfully defend|ed; and we have the greate&s;t incouragement to take this method for deliverance, whenever thought pro|per
<PB N="6" REF="014737_0006_0F94DB5479BDDC40">
by tho&s;e wi&s;e Men who are &s;et at the helm of affairs, and are appointed guardians for the &s;eve|ral Colonies&mdash;We mu&s;t break off all our &s;ins by righteou&s;ne&s;s, and our iniquities by &s;hewing mercy to the Poor;&mdash;then God will be for us, and all the powers of Earth and Hell will never deprive us of tho&s;e privileges. Now, <HI>What &s;hall we &s;ay to the&s;e things? If GOD be for us, who can be again&s;t us?</HI> If GOD be for us, he can ea&s;ily defeat the cruel de|&s;igns of our enemies many ways: He can rai&s;e a tempe&s;t in the &s;ea, that &s;hall to&s;s their &s;hipping to the heavens, and bury them in the depths, and hurl them back from whence they came, or to &s;ome other remote part of the earth, or da&s;h them one again&s;t another, or again&s;t &s;ome un&s;een reef in the &s;ea, and &s;ink them to the bottom. He can defeat them by &s;ending &s;ickne&s;s among them, and de&s;troy them by the pe&s;tilence, or by &s;ending faintne&s;s into their hearts, or granting us the victory if engaged in bat|tle. He that &s;its at the helm of all the affairs of the univer&s;e, and rules in the court of heaven above, can &s;o over-rule things in the court of <HI>Great-Britain,</HI> as to cau&s;e all tho&s;e cruel acts to be nullified, their &s;hipping and armies recalled, our &s;eaports all open|ed, <HI>Bo&s;ton</HI> and other places all re&s;tored to their pro|per owners, the great breach healed, that ancient union re&s;tored, and the Americans put into the po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of all their rights on a la&s;ting foundation.</P>
<P>THUS we &s;ee, my dear friends and countrymen, how many ways the ble&s;&s;ed GOD may interpo&s;e in our behalf&mdash;the la&s;t of which is to be the mo&s;t de|&s;ired by every American; for it &s;eems a pity the
<PB N="7" REF="014737_0007_0F94DB553A7948B8">
<HI>Engli&s;h</HI> nation &s;hould be broke like a potter's ve&s;&s;el; the nation whom God has exalted to heaven&mdash;in which has been more of the glory of God to be &s;een, than in all the nations in the world be&s;ides&mdash;the nation whom God has exalted to &s;uch glory, honor and dignity.&mdash;O Britons! why wilt thou ruin thy &s;elf, rip out thine own bowels, run the &s;word into thine own heart, undo thy &s;elf and thy mo&s;t obe|dient children, the mo&s;t loyal &s;ubjects in all thy va&s;t dominions! Why &s;houlde&s;t thou, who ha&s;t been the glory of all nations, become the reproach to all nations! Why wilt thou do that which will provoke God to ca&s;t off the nation forever, and withhold his glory forever! Thou who ha&s;t been the admiration of all foreigners for thy mo&s;t excellent con&s;titution, and ha&s;t excelled all nations for thy kindne&s;s and ho&s;pitality, even to &s;trangers! Witne&s;s the va&s;t num|bers of French and others in the City of London, from all parts of the world&mdash;di&s;tre&s;&s;ed &s;trangers and foreigners have been receiv'd with the greate&s;t kindne&s;s and indulgence.&mdash;Great numbers of French and others have been naturalized and permitted to &s;et up trade in the city of London, and have grown very rich thereby, by the unexampled beauty of the na|tives; for hither they came de&s;titute of every thing, and by public and private charity were put into a way to provide for them&s;elves and families. From the Revolution to this time, fifteen or twenty thou&s;and pounds has been paid to them annually by authori|ty, towards &s;upporting their poor. Now who could have thought the nation that has been &s;o full of kindne&s;s and benevolence to &s;trangers, could become
<PB N="8" REF="014737_0008_0F94DB55FA657680">
&s;o cruel to their own Children? Who could have thought a few years pa&s;t, that &s;aw the Engli&s;h nation in her meridian glory&mdash;that &s;aw the univer&s;ities in England, Oxford and Cambridge, which con&s;i&s;ted of near 40 Colleges, out of which proceeded &s;warms of the be&s;t men who have appeared mo&s;t eminent both in Church and &s;tate&mdash;that &s;aw the pre&s;ent King a&s;cending the throne to &s;way the Briti&s;h &s;cepter &mdash;that &s;aw the Proclamations i&s;&s;ued forth from un|der his royal hand and &s;eal, di&s;countenancing vice and immorality, and encouraging virtue and true religion. Who was there, 20 years pa&s;t, that be|held the harmony that &s;ub&s;i&s;ted between Britain and her Colonies&mdash;that &s;aw the wide Atlantick full of ve&s;&s;els laden with effects from America, bound to our native country&mdash;who could have thought, I &s;ay, that all the powers of Earth and Hell could have produced &s;o &s;udden an alteration, as to &s;ee the &s;ame ocean full of &s;hipping from our mother coun|try, bound to America, laden with &s;oldiers, arms and ammunition, and all manner of in&s;truments of death and cruelty, to de&s;troy her own Children! Who could have thought a little dete&s;table Tea, thrown into the ocean by a factious mob, &s;hould be the cau&s;e of an ocean of blood&s;hed, and forever di&s;&s;olve that union that was worth more Tea than the Ea&s;t-Indies produced? How much below the dignity of the nation are tho&s;e &s;evere proceedings? Con&s;ider, whil&s;t thou art pouring out thy hot thun|der bolts on the Americans, what thou art doing, le&s;t the Almighty God pour out his wrath on thee for every drop of Blood &s;hed in this unnatural con|trover&s;y,
<PB N="9" REF="014737_0009_0F94DB56B9D48508">
binds the cur&s;e of GOD on the nation, and will provoke GOD to leave it, and forever withdraw his glory from it never more to return, as he has from other nations and kingdoms. Methinks the words of the Prophet are applicable here, <HI>O thou &s;word of the Lord, how long will it be, ere thou wilt be quiet? Put up thy&s;elf into thy &s;cabbard, re&s;t and be &s;till</HI>&mdash;or turn thy&s;elf again&s;t &s;ome avowed enemy, not thy be&s;t friends: And tho&s;e of our Saviour, when he wept over the city of <HI>Jeru&s;alem,</HI> &s;aying, <HI>O Jeru&s;alem! had&s;t thou but known in this thy day the things that belong to thy peace; but now they are hid from thine eyes!</HI> And, <HI>O Jeru&s;alem! Jeru&s;alem! how often would I have gathered thee, as a hen gather|eth her chickens under her wings, and ye would not!</HI> And as in <HI>Ho&s;ea</HI> 9. 8. <HI>How &s;hall I give thee up, Ephraim! How &s;hall I deliver thee, I&s;rael! How &s;hall I make thee as Admah! How &s;hall I &s;et thee as Zeboim! My heart is turned within me, my repentings are kindled together!&mdash;How &s;hall I leave the nation whom I have taken into &s;uch a near relation to my&s;elf, and made comely thro' my comeline&s;s; which I have put upon high! Mu&s;t I leave her, as I have other nations and places!</HI>&mdash;How &s;hall I for&s;ake <HI>Great-Britain,</HI> as I have left <HI>Jeru&s;alem!&mdash;Go ye now into my place which was at Shiloh, and &s;ee what I did to it for the wickedne&s;s of my people I&s;rael.</HI>&mdash;Go ye thro'out all the ea&s;tern parts of the world, where they were once illuminated with the light of the glorious go&s;pel, and &s;ee how they are overwhelmed with ignorance, &s;uper&s;titions and here&s;ies&mdash;What I have done to the &s;even churches of <HI>A&s;ia</HI>&mdash;Look into <HI>Africa</HI>&mdash;time
<PB N="10" REF="014737_0010_0F94DB577AD02AE8">
was when there were thou&s;ands of glorious churches there&mdash;Into <HI>Europe,</HI> and &s;ee from how many places GOD has removed his glory.&mdash;There was once in <HI>Rome</HI> it&s;elf a glorious church.&mdash;Look into <HI>Spain,</HI> and the <HI>Spani&s;h</HI> low countries, which had once the glorious go&s;pel in them; but how has the bloody inqui&s;ition extingui&s;hed the light of the glorious go&s;pel in that unhappy kingdom!&mdash;Into <HI>Bohemia,</HI> and &s;ee now where is their glory?&mdash;Into <HI>Hungary,</HI> and the great kingdom of <HI>France</HI>; how has their wickedne&s;s provoked God to leave that unhappy kingdom!&mdash;Time was when there were hundreds of prote&s;tant mini&s;ters and churches there; but how has a <HI>Babyloni&s;h</HI> king made them an empty ve&s;&s;el, &s;wallowed them up like a dragon, and ca&s;t them out! And now, mu&s;t <HI>Great-Britain</HI> &s;hare the &s;ame fate? Mu&s;t <HI>Great-Britain</HI> come to nothing, to de&s;truction and di&s;&s;olution? for this is the certain fate of every kingdom divided again&s;t it&s;elf.&mdash;<HI>O that my head were waters, and mine eyes a fountain of tears, then would I weep day and night for the ruin of the</HI> Engli&s;h nation.&mdash;Is there no way to prevent this ruin?&mdash; Is there no balm in <HI>Gilead</HI>? no phy&s;ician there, for the healing this deadly wound?&mdash;Why wilt thou not hold out terms for reconciliation, and let the breach be healed?</P>
<P>O <HI>America!</HI> what is the cau&s;e of GOD's contro|ver&s;y with thee?&mdash;What ha&s;t thou done, that has provoked GOD to write his di&s;plea&s;ure again&s;t thee in &s;uch bloody and fiery corrections?&mdash;Can&s;t thou behold all the mi&s;ery that is come on thee, and im|magine thou ha&s;t done nothing to offend a holy,
<PB N="11" REF="014737_0011_0F94DB5839D3E8C8">
ju&s;t, and righteous GOD?&mdash;Can&s;t thou ca&s;t thine eye upon thy &s;eaports, from <HI>Falmouth</HI> to <HI>Carolina,</HI> and &s;ee the ocean full of engines of death, de&s;tined for the de&s;truction of <HI>America</HI>&mdash;look into <HI>Bo&s;ton,</HI> that fine metropolis&mdash;view it taken out of the hands of the proper owners&mdash;look into tho&s;e fine and beautiful hou&s;es, once devoted to the wor&s;hip and &s;ervice of GOD, once filled with his glorious pre&s;ence, now turned play-hou&s;es and riding-hou&s;es, places, to furni&s;h their hor&s;e for our de&s;truction!&mdash;Who was there that &s;aw the burning <HI>Charle&s;town</HI>&mdash;that &s;aw the flames a&s;cending from the lofty &s;teeples of tho&s;e beautiful buildings, once devoted to the wor|&s;hip of the great GOD;&mdash;I &s;ay, to &s;ee the flames a&s;|cending to the heavens&mdash;to hear the cracking and falling of the buildings&mdash;that heard the roaring of the cannon&mdash;the cries and groans of the wounded, they wallowing in their blood&mdash;the dead lying in heaps&mdash;look into <HI>Cambridge,</HI> and &s;ee tho&s;e colleges, which were once &s;eminaries of learning, places to fit and train up per&s;ons for the mo&s;t &s;acred work of the go&s;pel mini&s;try, and to be phy&s;icians for wounded immortal &s;ouls&mdash;I &s;ay, &s;hall we &s;ee tho&s;e colleges, that were once con&s;ecrated to this &s;acred and impor|tant bu&s;ine&s;s, now turned into ho&s;pitals, full of wounded bodies, and not &s;u&s;pect &s;omething has been ami&s;s in tho&s;e colleges?&mdash;See the ruin that has come on tho&s;e churches, and not &s;uppo&s;e there are things introduced contrary to the word of GOD, and very provoking to him?&mdash;Methinks we can have no greater precedent of the wrath of Almighty GOD, than the&s;e things are. Surely we can have no grea|ter
<PB N="12" REF="014737_0012_0F94DB58F989BC80">
evidence that our &s;ins have reached to heaven, and cry for vengeance upon us; and that he will not be for us, but again&s;t us, unle&s;s we turn to him by unfeigned repentance: For &s;o long as we hold fa&s;t our &s;ins, and retain our iniquities, and do not turn to GOD, do not regard the works of the LORD, nor the operation of his hands, notwith&s;tanding he has been &s;peaking to us by terrible things in righ|teou&s;ne&s;s&mdash;been threatning us with drought and &s;ore &s;ickne&s;s&mdash;taking away many by death;&mdash;and now, add to all this the withdrawing of GOD's holy Spi|rit&mdash;&s;u&s;pence of divine influence&mdash;hardne&s;s of heart &mdash;blindne&s;s of mind;&mdash;Now, all the&s;e together, makes it very evident there never was a people nigher the brink of final ruin than we are; and as long as we continue in this carele&s;s, &s;tupid, and indifferent &s;tate, we declare by our practice, we have not done ami&s;s, our ways are equal, we have not done any thing to merit tho&s;e evils from the hand of the Lord. We an&s;wer by our practice, as <HI>Pharaoh</HI> an&s;wered <HI>Mo&s;es, Who is the Lord, that we &s;hould obey him?</HI>&mdash; By this means we reflect infinite di&s;honor on the wi&s;e Governor of the univer&s;e, for puni&s;hing an in|nocent people. And here ari&s;es the controver&s;y be|tween the great GOD and us&mdash;ju&s;t as when a kind father corrects a rebellious child, his aim is to bring him to obedience, and to his duty; now if the child is regardle&s;s of his father's corrections, and will not turn for the &s;tripes his father gives him, there is an ab&s;olute nece&s;&s;ity for a more &s;evere correction;&mdash; and if he will not finally turn, he ca&s;ts him off as a rebel, and lets him go on, and fill up the mea&s;ure
<PB N="13" REF="014737_0013_0F94DB59BB11C3E0">
of his cup: But if the child turns to his father, and to his obedience, the father's heart is full of pity, his bowels yearn with compa&s;&s;ion, his arms are open to receive him, and treat him with the mo&s;t parental affection.&mdash;Ju&s;t &s;o the ble&s;&s;ed GOD has for many years been dealing with <HI>America</HI>&mdash;he has been ma|nife&s;ting his &s;ore di&s;plea&s;ure again&s;t us&mdash;he has been mo&s;t &s;everely correcting us&mdash;his &s;tripes have been mo&s;t &s;everely laid upon us.&mdash;Now, if we &s;till go on, and will not remove the cau&s;e of his controver&s;y, there is a nece&s;&s;ity of his &s;tripes being laid on more &s;evere; for GOD never began a controver&s;y with any people, that ever ended in any thing &s;hort of their reformation or final ruin. And this is the ca&s;e with us. If we turn to GOD, put away tho&s;e laws, cu&s;toms and practices, tho&s;e &s;ins and abominations that are the cau&s;e of his controver&s;y, and turn to him by unfeigned repentance, take his word for our rule, &s;hake the du&s;t from off our bibles, and let this be the compa&s;s to &s;teer our cour&s;e by, and walk &s;o that our ways plea&s;e the LORD; our calamities will &s;oon cea&s;e, our enemies will be at peace with us, the great and eternal GOD will be for us and on our &s;ide. 'Tis in this way, and no other, that we can have the LORD for us. Thus it was when God puni&s;hed <HI>I&s;rael</HI> with three years famine, king <HI>David</HI> was very &s;olicitous to know the cau&s;e of GOD's anger; and no &s;ooner had he found out, and done as the LORD required in this matter, the heavens could no longer withhold the rain, the earth was repleni&s;hed, and bro't forth her fruit. So it was with <HI>Jo&s;hua,</HI> after his defeat at <HI>Ai.</HI> The next &s;tep he takes, is to
<PB N="14" REF="014737_0014_0F94DB5A7997B6A0">
&s;earch after the cau&s;e of GOD's anger; and as &s;oon as he had put the accu&s;ed thing out of the camp, GOD was for him, and with him, and his enemies could not &s;tand before him. In like manner, when the mariners had taken <HI>Jonah</HI> into their &s;hip, it cau|&s;ed a terrible &s;torm in the &s;ea, which mounted her to the heavens, and buried her in the depths, and filled them with dreadful di&s;tre&s;s; they were very &s;olicitous to know the cau&s;e of GOD's anger, and as &s;oon as they had thrown <HI>Jonah</HI> overboard, the &s;ea was a perfect calm.&mdash;So it would be with <HI>America</HI>&mdash; Could we find out the cau&s;e, and throw the <HI>Jonah</HI> overboard, the nation would be in a perfect calm, and GOD will certainly be for us, and on our &s;ide.</P>
<P>Which brings us to the</P>
<P N="3">III. And la&s;t thing propo&s;ed; that is, to &s;hew <HI>How ble&s;&s;ed we &s;hall be if the ble&s;&s;ed</HI> GOD <HI>be for us.</HI></P>
<P>AND now, <HI>What &s;hall we &s;ay to the&s;e things?&mdash;If God be for us, who can be again&s;t us?</HI>&mdash;He will be a wall of fire round about us, and the glory in the mid&s;t of us:&mdash;He will defend us from all the in&s;ults of men or devils.&mdash;All tho&s;e wi&s;e and good men, who are at the helm of affairs, and are appointed guardians for the colonies, if they are in&s;trumental of a thorough and univer&s;al reformation, will &s;hine as lights in the world; their memories will be dear and precious to the late&s;t po&s;terity; and they will not only &s;hine in this world, but in the world to come, in the kingdom of glory, as &s;tars of the fir&s;t magni|tude&mdash;Tho&s;e churches in this land will be favored with the divine pre&s;ence and glory of GOD&mdash;We &s;hall be ble&s;&s;ed in our ba&s;ket and &s;tore, in our goings
<PB N="15" REF="014737_0015_0F94DB5B396AAB60">
out and comings in&mdash;We &s;hall no longer hear the &s;ound of the trumpet, or alarm of war, nor &s;ee garments rolled in blood&mdash;tho&s;e in&s;truments of cruelty &s;hall be turned into the harmle&s;s uten&s;ils of hu&s;bandry&mdash;We &s;hall be ble&s;&s;ed with both peace and plenty&mdash;a foundation will be laid to enjoy them to the late&s;t po&s;terity&mdash;our root &s;hall be &s;pread by the waters, and the dew &s;hall lie on our branches&mdash; We &s;hall enjoy all tho&s;e privileges that CHRIST has purcha&s;ed for us, and which we have in con&s;equence of that eternal covenant that was made between God the Father and God the Son; which covenant was ratified in the coun&s;el of his eternal peace and was fulfilled when he &s;hed his precious blood on the cro&s;s; through which channel flows every mercy and every favor that ever any of the human race ever did or ever will enjoy; for all was lo&s;t by the fall and apo&s;tacy of our fir&s;t head and repre&s;entative, and all was purcha&s;ed by our &s;econd; and in this &s;en&s;e, and this only, he is &s;aid to be the Saviour of all men.&mdash;Now, if GOD be for us, all tho&s;e mercies will as naturally flow to us, as the rivers flow into the &s;ea.&mdash;Now, <HI>What &s;hall we &s;ay to the&s;e things?&mdash; If GOD be for us, who can be again&s;t us?</HI>&mdash;Surely, if GOD be for us, we need not apply to <HI>France, Spain,</HI> or <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> for protection; for the ble&s;&s;ed GOD will protect us.</P>
<P>THUS we have con&s;idered the importance of having GOD for us&mdash;We con&s;idered what mu&s;t ab&s;olutely be done, that GOD may be for us&mdash; And likewi&s;e, how ble&s;&s;ed it will be to have GOD for us.</P>
<P><PB N="16" REF="014737_0016_0F94DB5BF91E7790">AND now, my dear friends and countrymen, <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="indecipherable" EXTENT="1 word"> we are all concerned in this mo&s;t &s;olemn affair, how highly does it become us, to endeavor to remove every impediment that hinders GOD's being for us, and on our &s;ide!</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>A HEARTY FRIEND TO ALL THE COLONIES.</SIGNED> <DATELINE>Norwich</DATELINE></CLOSER>
